      <title>Checks and Balances - GovTrack.us</title>
      <link>https://www.govtrack.us/posts/427/2024-06-28_checks-and-balances</link>
      <guid isPermaLink="true">https://www.govtrack.us/posts/427/2024-06-28_checks-and-balances</guid>
      <description>&lt;div id="content"&gt; 				 			   	  				 &lt;h1&gt;Checks and Balances&lt;/h1&gt;  &lt;div class="row"&gt;     &lt;div class="col-md order-md-2" style="margin-bottom: 2em"&gt;         &lt;div class="ms-md-3" style="border: 1px solid #777; border-radius: 1em; padding: 1em; background-color: #F9F9F9;"&gt;         &lt;h2&gt;Get Legislative Recap Updates In Your Inbox!&lt;/h2&gt;         &lt;p&gt;Sign up (it&amp;rsquo;s free!) to get posts like this straight to your inbox. You&amp;rsquo;ll be able to choose posts from these categories:&lt;/p&gt;         &lt;p&gt;Legislative Recap &amp;nbsp; &amp;ndash; &amp;nbsp; Legislative Preview &amp;nbsp; &amp;ndash; &amp;nbsp; Analysis and Commentary &amp;nbsp; &amp;ndash; &amp;nbsp; News About GovTrack &amp;nbsp; &amp;ndash; &amp;nbsp; Using GovTrack Tips&lt;/p&gt;         &lt;p&gt;&lt;a href="https://www.govtrack.us/accounts/lists" class="btn btn-primary"&gt;Sign Up &amp;raquo;&lt;/a&gt;&lt;/p&gt;         &lt;/div&gt;     &lt;/div&gt;      &lt;div class="col-md"&gt;        &lt;p&gt;           Jun 28, 2024           &amp;middot; by Amy West       &lt;/p&gt;        &lt;p&gt;This week the House passed four bills and the Supreme Court established a new standard for how bills should be written if the topic covers something that might lead to regulation.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;h2&gt;Checks (Mostly)&lt;/h2&gt; &lt;p&gt;&lt;a href="https://www.govtrack.us/congress/bills/118/hr7152"&gt;H.R. 7152: Divided Families National Registry Act&lt;/a&gt; which would create a registry of U.S. families with members in North Korea in order to facilitate bringing those members out of North Korea passed &lt;a href="https://www.govtrack.us/congress/votes/118-2024/h281"&gt;375-8&lt;/a&gt;.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;N.B.: links on vote totals go to the House Press Gallery X account because they are not yet in our system.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;ul&gt; &lt;li&gt;&lt;a href="https://www.govtrack.us/congress/bills/118/hr8774"&gt;H.R. 8774: Department of Defense Appropriations Act, 2025&lt;/a&gt; passed &lt;a href="https://x.com/HouseDailyPress/status/1806699256129929395"&gt;217-198&lt;/a&gt;&lt;/li&gt; &lt;li&gt;&lt;a href="https://www.govtrack.us/congress/bills/118/hr8752"&gt;H.R. 8752: Department of Homeland Security Appropriations Act, 2025&lt;/a&gt; passed &lt;a href="https://x.com/HouseDailyPress/status/1806702581382619215"&gt;212-203&lt;/a&gt;&lt;/li&gt; &lt;li&gt;&lt;a href="https://www.govtrack.us/congress/bills/118/hr8771"&gt;H.R. 8771: Department of State, Foreign Operations, and Related Programs Appropriations Act, 2025&lt;/a&gt; passed &lt;a href="https://x.com/HouseDailyPress/status/1806705766893588683"&gt;212-200&lt;/a&gt;&lt;/li&gt; &lt;/ul&gt; &lt;p&gt;The White House has released statements for &lt;a href="https://www.whitehouse.gov/omb/statements-of-administration-policy/"&gt;all three appropriations bills saying that they would veto them&lt;/a&gt; as currently written.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;h2&gt;Balances?&lt;/h2&gt; &lt;p&gt;Since 1984, &lt;a href="https://www.law.cornell.edu/wex/chevron_deference"&gt;the position of the Supreme Court, and thus all lower courts,&lt;/a&gt; has been that when Congress passes a bill that allows for interpretation in setting up regulations, courts should defer to the agency's interpretation if it's reasonable.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;Today, &lt;a href="https://www.supremecourt.gov/opinions/23pdf/22-451_7m58.pdf"&gt;the Supreme Court overturned that position&lt;/a&gt; (colloquially known as "Chevron deference"). This means that either Congress must start writing much more specific legislation or courts get to overrule agencies when they think the agencies are wrong. The problem is that typically regulations are constructed by people with very specific expertise. Examples of regulation include food safety, drug safety, energy safety, occupational safety, air pollution, water pollution, and financial markets. Now, instead of deferring to agency staff who have professional expertise in the relevant areas, courts can make their own decisions even if no one in a given court has any expertise themselves.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;It's not clear exactly what the scope of the effect of this decision will be yet. In theory, Congress could start writing much more specific and explicit legislation. If Congress took that path, it would render what is otherwise a substantial expansion of judicial power moot. We will all just have to wait and see whether that actually occurs.&lt;/p&gt;      &lt;/div&gt; &lt;/div&gt;  &lt;hr&gt;  &lt;p&gt;    Let us know what you think about these updates    by tooting us on &lt;a rel="me" href="https://mastodon.social/@GovTrack" title="Mastodon"&gt;&lt;i class="fab fa-mastodon"&gt;&lt;/i&gt; Mastodon&lt;/a&gt;    or &lt;a href="https://www.govtrack.us/contact" style="text-decoration: none"&gt;&lt;i class="fas fa-envelope"&gt;&lt;/i&gt; sending us an email&lt;/a&gt;. &lt;/p&gt;    			&lt;/div&gt;</description>
      <media:content url="https://www.govtrack.us/static/images/media_icon.png?20230729" type="image/png"/>
    </item>
    <item>
      <title>More Appropriations - GovTrack.us</title>
      <link>https://www.govtrack.us/posts/426/2024-06-24_more-appropriations</link>
      <guid isPermaLink="true">https://www.govtrack.us/posts/426/2024-06-24_more-appropriations</guid>
      <description>&lt;div id="content"&gt; 				 			   	  				 &lt;h1&gt;More Appropriations&lt;/h1&gt;  &lt;div class="row"&gt;     &lt;div class="col-md order-md-2" style="margin-bottom: 2em"&gt;         &lt;div class="ms-md-3" style="border: 1px solid #777; border-radius: 1em; padding: 1em; background-color: #F9F9F9;"&gt;         &lt;h2&gt;Get Legislative Preview Updates In Your Inbox!&lt;/h2&gt;         &lt;p&gt;Sign up (it&amp;rsquo;s free!) to get posts like this straight to your inbox. You&amp;rsquo;ll be able to choose posts from these categories:&lt;/p&gt;         &lt;p&gt;Legislative Recap &amp;nbsp; &amp;ndash; &amp;nbsp; Legislative Preview &amp;nbsp; &amp;ndash; &amp;nbsp; Analysis and Commentary &amp;nbsp; &amp;ndash; &amp;nbsp; News About GovTrack &amp;nbsp; &amp;ndash; &amp;nbsp; Using GovTrack Tips&lt;/p&gt;         &lt;p&gt;&lt;a href="https://www.govtrack.us/accounts/lists" class="btn btn-primary"&gt;Sign Up &amp;raquo;&lt;/a&gt;&lt;/p&gt;         &lt;/div&gt;     &lt;/div&gt;      &lt;div class="col-md"&gt;        &lt;p&gt;           Jun 24, 2024           &amp;middot; by Daniel Schuman       &lt;/p&gt;        &lt;p&gt;Hello Trackers!&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;We’re getting close to August recess, which is an extended period of time when neither the House nor the Senate are in session. That doesn’t mean nobody’s working, but it does mean no legislation will move on the floor and committees largely won’t be meeting. Also, election season is here in earnest. For 2024, that’s the Presidential election, all 435 House Seats and ⅓ of the Senate (aka “&lt;a href="https://www.senate.gov/senators/Class_I.htm"&gt;Class 1&lt;/a&gt;”). &lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;The House of Representatives&lt;/strong&gt; is in session this week (&lt;a href="https://www.majorityleader.gov/uploadedfiles/2024_house_calendar_-_one_page_-_revised_april_2024.pdf"&gt;6/24-6/28&lt;/a&gt;), but then out until July 8. After that, they’re back for July (except the week of July 15th for the GOP convention) and then it’s the August Recess (starting 8/2) until September 9th.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;The Senate&lt;/strong&gt; is not in session this week or next week, but otherwise, they’re on a very similar schedule for July &amp;amp; August. They too return on September 9th.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;The new fiscal year starts on October 1st&lt;/strong&gt;, which means all twelve appropriations bills must be law, and if not, a continuing resolution must be passed or the government will shut down. That’s not a lot of time, and given the politics of the situation, it’s most likely that Congress will pass a short term &lt;a href="https://www.gao.gov/blog/what-continuing-resolution-and-how-does-it-impact-government-operations"&gt;continuing resolution&lt;/a&gt; to keep the lights on until they can reach an agreement. That long term agreement most likely won’t be struck until after the election, when members know the configuration of the next Congress and are no longer afraid of negatively influencing the upcoming election.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;The main priority for the House of Representatives &lt;a href="https://www.majorityleader.gov/schedule/weekly-schedule.htm"&gt;this week&lt;/a&gt; is appropriations. Three bills are scheduled for floor consideration pursuant to a rule, which means that they need only a simple majority vote to advance in the chamber, and they are appropriations for Homeland Security, the Department of State, and the Department of Defense.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;The House Rules Committee, which sets the rules of debate on the House floor, is &lt;a href="https://rules.house.gov/news/announcement/meeting-announcement-june-25-2024"&gt;scheduled to meet&lt;/a&gt; on Tuesday to consider all three bills. They will decide whether to allow members of the entire chamber to vote upon some of the &lt;a href="https://rules.house.gov/bill/118/hr-FY2025-HomelandSecurity"&gt;233 proposed amendments&lt;/a&gt; to the Homeland Security appropriations bill, the &lt;a href="https://rules.house.gov/bill/118/hr-FY2025-SFOPS"&gt;219 proposed amendments&lt;/a&gt; to the Department of State appropriations bill, and the &lt;a href="https://rules.house.gov/bill/118/hr-FY2025-Defense"&gt;401 proposed amendments&lt;/a&gt; to the Defense Department appropriations bills. The number of amendments might change before Tuesday.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;Also scheduled for floor consideration, but under suspension — which requires a 2/3s vote — are six bills that appear to be thematically connected to foreign affairs.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;The House of Representatives has &lt;a href="https://www.congress.gov/committee-schedule/weekly/2024/06/24"&gt;41 committee meetings&lt;/a&gt; scheduled for this week. Five of them are subcommittee markups for appropriations bills: Commerce, Justice Science; Department of Labor, Health and Human Services; Department of Transportation, Housing and Urban Development; Interior and Environment; and Energy and Water. After they’re favorably reported by the subcommittee, we can anticipate that they will soon be considered by the full committee and then advance to the chamber floor before the August recess.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;Since Congress will be out of session next week, the next preview will be July 8th. We’re not on recess though, so we’ll use these off weeks to address questions we’ve gotten from users over the last few months.&lt;/p&gt;      &lt;/div&gt; &lt;/div&gt;  &lt;hr&gt;  &lt;p&gt;    Let us know what you think about these updates    by tooting us on &lt;a rel="me" href="https://mastodon.social/@GovTrack" title="Mastodon"&gt;&lt;i class="fab fa-mastodon"&gt;&lt;/i&gt; Mastodon&lt;/a&gt;    or &lt;a href="https://www.govtrack.us/contact" style="text-decoration: none"&gt;&lt;i class="fas fa-envelope"&gt;&lt;/i&gt; sending us an email&lt;/a&gt;. &lt;/p&gt;    			&lt;/div&gt;</description>
      <media:content url="https://www.govtrack.us/static/images/media_icon.png?20230729" type="image/png"/>
    </item>
    <item>
      <title>Inaugural Mailbag - GovTrack.us</title>
      <link>https://www.govtrack.us/posts/425/2024-06-21_inaugural-mailbag</link>
      <guid isPermaLink="true">https://www.govtrack.us/posts/425/2024-06-21_inaugural-mailbag</guid>
      <description>&lt;div id="content"&gt; 				 			   	  				 &lt;h1&gt;Inaugural Mailbag&lt;/h1&gt;  &lt;div class="row"&gt;     &lt;div class="col-md order-md-2" style="margin-bottom: 2em"&gt;         &lt;div class="ms-md-3" style="border: 1px solid #777; border-radius: 1em; padding: 1em; background-color: #F9F9F9;"&gt;         &lt;h2&gt;Get Analysis and Commentary Updates In Your Inbox!&lt;/h2&gt;         &lt;p&gt;Sign up (it&amp;rsquo;s free!) to get posts like this straight to your inbox. You&amp;rsquo;ll be able to choose posts from these categories:&lt;/p&gt;         &lt;p&gt;Legislative Recap &amp;nbsp; &amp;ndash; &amp;nbsp; Legislative Preview &amp;nbsp; &amp;ndash; &amp;nbsp; Analysis and Commentary &amp;nbsp; &amp;ndash; &amp;nbsp; News About GovTrack &amp;nbsp; &amp;ndash; &amp;nbsp; Using GovTrack Tips&lt;/p&gt;         &lt;p&gt;&lt;a href="https://www.govtrack.us/accounts/lists" class="btn btn-primary"&gt;Sign Up &amp;raquo;&lt;/a&gt;&lt;/p&gt;         &lt;/div&gt;     &lt;/div&gt;      &lt;div class="col-md"&gt;        &lt;p&gt;           Jun 21, 2024           &amp;middot; by Amy West       &lt;/p&gt;        &lt;h2&gt;Mailbag! And one new law!&lt;/h2&gt; &lt;p&gt;We plan to start using recess weeks to do posts addressing comments and questions we get by email and from a survey we sent out recently. In the future, these will be joint posts from me &amp;amp; Daniel, but for today I'm going to address two questions we got that &lt;em&gt;aren't&lt;/em&gt; about Congress.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;However, before we start that, the Senate was in this week and passed &lt;a href="https://www.govtrack.us/congress/bills/118/s870"&gt;S. 870: A bill to authorize appropriations for the United States Fire Administration and firefighter assistance grant programs, to advance the benefits of nuclear energy, and for other purposes&lt;/a&gt; by &lt;a href="https://www.govtrack.us/congress/votes/118-2024/s200"&gt;88-2&lt;/a&gt;. The bill is about what it says it is in the title and had been modified in the House already. The Senate accepted those changes with this vote and now it goes to the President for signing.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;h2&gt;What is Treason?&lt;/h2&gt; &lt;p&gt;We were asked why hadn't a particular politician been charged with treason. The short answer is that &lt;a href="https://www.archives.gov/founding-docs/constitution-transcript"&gt;Article 3, Section 3 of the Constitution&lt;/a&gt; defines treason in a very specific way in order to limit bad faith uses of it:&lt;/p&gt; &lt;blockquote&gt; &lt;p&gt;Treason against the United States, shall consist only in levying War against them, or in adhering to their Enemies, giving them Aid and Comfort. No Person shall be convicted of Treason unless on the Testimony of two Witnesses to the same overt Act, or on Confession in open Court.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;/blockquote&gt; &lt;p&gt;So, for an act to be treasonous, we need to be at war, and the person committing it needs to, in some way, aid the enemy. The only instance that really comes close to this in recent memory was when &lt;a href="https://www.nytimes.com/2016/12/31/opinion/sunday/nixons-vietnam-treachery.html"&gt;Richard Nixon attempted to get South Vietnam to reject peace overtures&lt;/a&gt; from the Johnson Administration towards the North Vietnamese  in 1968. NIxon felt that successful peace negotiations would hurt his chances for election that year. Since Nixon was using back channels to communicate with the South Vietnamese, our allies, rather than the North Vietnamese, and since even if he hadn't interfered, there's no way to know if the negotiations would have worked out it's not treason as defined above.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;The linked article does suggest Nixon's actions violated a different law, but we'll never know if that would have held up in court since no one ever pursued charges. It didn't even become public until decades after the 1968 election.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;h2&gt;The Federal Register (FR) &amp;amp; the Code of Federal Regulations (CFR)&lt;/h2&gt; &lt;p&gt;Another person asked which was better for tracking bills: the Federal Register (FR) or the Code of Federal Regulations (CFR).&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;The answer is neither will help in tracking bills because those publications address a different stage in lawmaking that belongs to the Executive Branch and only happens once laws have been passed.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;The extremely simplified version is this: Congress passes a law saying that they want X to happen. Then, the relevant agency in the Executive Branch sits down to figure out &lt;em&gt;how&lt;/em&gt; to make it happen. The first draft of that how - aka the first draft of a regulation - is published in the &lt;a href="https://www.federalregister.gov/"&gt;Federal Register&lt;/a&gt;. The public then has some period of time to comment, the agency reviews the comments, and then a final draft - aka the regulation itself - is published both in the FR and added to the correct location in the &lt;a href="https://www.ecfr.gov/"&gt;Code of Federal Regulations (CFR)&lt;/a&gt;. The correct location is based on subject. For example, if the regulation is about agriculture, then it'll appear in &lt;a href="https://www.ecfr.gov/current/title-7"&gt;Title (aka chapter) 7&lt;/a&gt;.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;Another way to view regulations is on &lt;a href="https://www.regulations.gov/"&gt;Regulations.gov&lt;/a&gt;. It lets you know not only what's currently in process, but you can also view public comments on a proposed regulation. This site also gives users references to where in the CFR the proposed regulation will end up. For example, here's a &lt;a href="https://www.regulations.gov/document/DEA-2024-0059-0001"&gt;proposed rule to downgrade marijuana in the Controlled Substances List&lt;/a&gt;. You can view all 24,147 comments on it, see where it'll go in the CFR and of course, read the proposed rule.&lt;/p&gt;      &lt;/div&gt; &lt;/div&gt;  &lt;hr&gt;  &lt;p&gt;    Let us know what you think about these updates    by tooting us on &lt;a rel="me" href="https://mastodon.social/@GovTrack" title="Mastodon"&gt;&lt;i class="fab fa-mastodon"&gt;&lt;/i&gt; Mastodon&lt;/a&gt;    or &lt;a href="https://www.govtrack.us/contact" style="text-decoration: none"&gt;&lt;i class="fas fa-envelope"&gt;&lt;/i&gt; sending us an email&lt;/a&gt;. &lt;/p&gt;    			&lt;/div&gt;</description>
      <media:content url="https://www.govtrack.us/static/images/media_icon.png?20230729" type="image/png"/>
    </item>
