      <title>Authorizations, Contempt &amp; Hearings - GovTrack.us</title>
      <link>https://www.govtrack.us/posts/422/2024-06-11_authorizations-contempt-hearings</link>
      <guid isPermaLink="true">https://www.govtrack.us/posts/422/2024-06-11_authorizations-contempt-hearings</guid>
      <description>&lt;div id="content"&gt; 				 			   	  				 &lt;h1&gt;Authorizations, Contempt &amp;amp; Hearings&lt;/h1&gt;  &lt;div class="row"&gt;     &lt;div class="col-md order-md-2" style="margin-bottom: 2em"&gt;         &lt;div class="ms-md-3" style="border: 1px solid #777; border-radius: 1em; padding: 1em; background-color: #F9F9F9;"&gt;         &lt;h2&gt;Get Legislative Preview Updates In Your Inbox!&lt;/h2&gt;         &lt;p&gt;Sign up (it&amp;rsquo;s free!) to get posts like this straight to your inbox. You&amp;rsquo;ll be able to choose posts from these categories:&lt;/p&gt;         &lt;p&gt;Legislative Recap &amp;nbsp; &amp;ndash; &amp;nbsp; Legislative Preview &amp;nbsp; &amp;ndash; &amp;nbsp; Analysis and Commentary &amp;nbsp; &amp;ndash; &amp;nbsp; News About GovTrack &amp;nbsp; &amp;ndash; &amp;nbsp; Using GovTrack Tips&lt;/p&gt;         &lt;p&gt;&lt;a href="https://www.govtrack.us/accounts/lists" class="btn btn-primary"&gt;Sign Up &amp;raquo;&lt;/a&gt;&lt;/p&gt;         &lt;/div&gt;     &lt;/div&gt;      &lt;div class="col-md"&gt;        &lt;p&gt;           Jun 11, 2024           &amp;middot; by Daniel Schuman       &lt;/p&gt;        &lt;p&gt;Hello Trackers!&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;The House of Representatives&lt;/strong&gt; has a &lt;a href="https://www.majorityleader.gov/schedule/weekly-schedule.htm"&gt;busy week&lt;/a&gt; this week.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;There are two substantive bills set for consideration on the House floor under regular order, which requires a majority vote of the members on the floor for passage. The first is the &lt;a href="https://www.govtrack.us/congress/bills/118/hr8070"&gt;National Defense Authorization Act&lt;/a&gt; and it is a whopping 1,008 pages. Members of Congress proposed &lt;a href="https://rules.house.gov/bill/118/hr-8070"&gt;1,357 amendments to the bill&lt;/a&gt;, and the House Rules committee will recommend today which of those amendments will be eligible to be considered on the floor. The NDAA is considered one of the few must-pass bills — it authorizes the activities of the Department of Defense, setting maximum funding levels and establishing various policies — and it is used as a vehicle to carry many other bills into law that otherwise would not have an opportunity to be considered. It will take hours for the House of Representatives to consider the legislation and amendments thereto.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;The second substantive bill to be considered under regular order is a &lt;a href="https://www.govinfo.gov/content/pkg/CRPT-118hrpt527/pdf/CRPT-118hrpt527.pdf"&gt;resolution&lt;/a&gt; to find Attorney General Merrick Garland in contempt of Congress for not providing video in response to a subpoena of Pres. Biden’s interview with Special Counsel Hur.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;There are eleven bills on suspension in the House of Representatives, which means they need a 2/3s vote of members present to pass that chamber. They range the gamut from addressing employment for persons with disabilities to providing a congressional gold medal to diplomats who helped Jewish people escape the Holocaust to labeling certain products with a warning that they are not to be flushed.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;House committees&lt;/strong&gt; have &lt;a href="https://www.congress.gov/committee-schedule/weekly/2024/06/10?q=%7B%22chamber%22%3A%22House%22%7D"&gt;36 meetings&lt;/a&gt; scheduled this week, with four each before the Veterans’ Affairs and Transportation and Infrastructure committees. I’d note that the House Intelligence Committee is holding a closed markup of the FY 2025 Intelligence Authorization Act, the legislation that governs the activities of the intelligence community. (A markup is when the committee considers legislation and decides whether to report it to the full chamber). The Intel Bill is often added onto the NDAA for passage.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;Also note a handful of appropriations markups, including full committee consideration on Thursday of three appropriations bills concerning Defense, Financial Services and General Government, and the Legislative Branch. What this means is that the subcommittee already has favorably reported the legislation and now the bill’s text will be considered by the full committee. At issue is whether Republicans will add measures to the legislation, sometimes called poison pills, that makes them unpassable. Note that the Agriculture and State &amp;amp; Foreign Operations appropriations subcommittees will also hold markups. &lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;There’s also a scheduled hearing on Thursday before the House Judiciary Committee concerning the Manhattan District Attorney’s Office, but &lt;a href="https://www.nbcnewyork.com/news/local/manhattan-da-agrees-to-testify-in-congress-but-likely-not-until-trump-is-sentenced/5488470/"&gt;news reports&lt;/a&gt; suggest that the requested witness, Alvin Bragg, will decline to testify until after Pres. Trump is sentenced.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;The Senate&lt;/strong&gt; reconvenes on Tuesday and the &lt;a href="https://www.democrats.senate.gov/2024/06/05/schedule-for-pro-forma-session-and-tuesday-june-11-2024"&gt;only information officially available&lt;/a&gt; suggests that it will consider a nominee to the Federal Energy Regulatory Committee.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Senate committees&lt;/strong&gt; are holding &lt;a href="https://www.congress.gov/committee-schedule/weekly/2024/06/10?q=%7B%22chamber%22%3A%22Senate%22%7D"&gt;28 meetings this week&lt;/a&gt;, with ten of them before the Armed Services Committee. The Armed Services Committee is working through its version of the National Defense Authorization Act, with subcommittee markups scheduled in closed session for all of its subcommittees, and full committee consideration of the NDAA set for Thursday and Friday. Relatedly, on Wednesday the Defense Appropriations subcommittee will consider appropriations for the CIA and National Security Agency on Wednesday. Perhaps coincidentally, the Senate Homeland Security and Governmental Affairs Committee on Tuesday will hold an &lt;a href="https://www.congress.gov/event/118th-congress/senate-event/335892?s=3&amp;amp;r=1"&gt;oversight hearing on sexual assault and harassment in the Coast Guard&lt;/a&gt;.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;Also on Wednesday a &lt;a href="https://www.congress.gov/event/118th-congress/senate-event/335900?s=2&amp;amp;r=12"&gt;Senate Judiciary Subcommittee will look at abortion bans and interstate travel&lt;/a&gt;. On Thursday the Financial Services and General Government appropriations subcommittee will &lt;a href="https://www.congress.gov/event/118th-congress/senate-event/335906?s=1&amp;amp;r=4"&gt;hear testimony from the Securities and Exchange Commission concerning their proposed budget&lt;/a&gt;, and the Senate Commerce Committee will hold a hearing on &lt;a href="https://www.congress.gov/event/118th-congress/senate-event/335904?s=1&amp;amp;r=3"&gt;FAA oversight of aviation&lt;/a&gt;.&lt;/p&gt;      &lt;/div&gt; &lt;/div&gt;  &lt;hr&gt;  &lt;p&gt;    Let us know what you think about these updates    by tooting us on &lt;a rel="me" href="https://mastodon.social/@GovTrack" title="Mastodon"&gt;&lt;i class="fab fa-mastodon"&gt;&lt;/i&gt; Mastodon&lt;/a&gt;    or &lt;a href="https://www.govtrack.us/contact" style="text-decoration: none"&gt;&lt;i class="fas fa-envelope"&gt;&lt;/i&gt; sending us an email&lt;/a&gt;. &lt;/p&gt;    			&lt;/div&gt;</description>
