      <title>Congress works on funding the government this week - GovTrack.us</title>
      <link>https://www.govtrack.us/posts/420/2024-06-04_congress-works-on-funding-the-government-this-week</link>
      <guid isPermaLink="true">https://www.govtrack.us/posts/420/2024-06-04_congress-works-on-funding-the-government-this-week</guid>
      <description>&lt;div id="content"&gt; 				 			   	  				 &lt;h1&gt;Congress works on funding the government this week&lt;/h1&gt;  &lt;div class="row"&gt;     &lt;div class="col-md order-md-2" style="margin-bottom: 2em"&gt;         &lt;div class="ms-md-3" style="border: 1px solid #777; border-radius: 1em; padding: 1em; background-color: #F9F9F9;"&gt;         &lt;h2&gt;Get Legislative Preview Updates In Your Inbox!&lt;/h2&gt;         &lt;p&gt;Sign up (it&amp;rsquo;s free!) to get posts like this straight to your inbox. You&amp;rsquo;ll be able to choose posts from these categories:&lt;/p&gt;         &lt;p&gt;Legislative Recap &amp;nbsp; &amp;ndash; &amp;nbsp; Legislative Preview &amp;nbsp; &amp;ndash; &amp;nbsp; Analysis and Commentary &amp;nbsp; &amp;ndash; &amp;nbsp; News About GovTrack &amp;nbsp; &amp;ndash; &amp;nbsp; Using GovTrack Tips&lt;/p&gt;         &lt;p&gt;&lt;a href="https://www.govtrack.us/accounts/lists" class="btn btn-primary"&gt;Sign Up &amp;raquo;&lt;/a&gt;&lt;/p&gt;         &lt;/div&gt;     &lt;/div&gt;      &lt;div class="col-md"&gt;        &lt;p&gt;           Jun 4, 2024           &amp;middot; by Daniel Schuman       &lt;/p&gt;        &lt;p&gt;We can expect the pace of matters in Congress to accelerate as we get closer to its summer recess at the end of July, although much of the time for serious legislation --- except appropriations and national defense --- has ended until after the election.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;The House of Representatives has a &lt;a href="https://www.majorityleader.gov/schedule/weekly-schedule.htm"&gt;very light floor schedule&lt;/a&gt; this week.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;There are two substantive bills that will be considered on the floor. We will see the first of twelve appropriations bills, concerning &lt;a href="https://www.govinfo.gov/content/pkg/BILLS-118hr8580rh/pdf/BILLS-118hr8580rh.pdf"&gt;Military Construction and Veterans Affairs&lt;/a&gt;. This is usually a non-controversial bill, but House Republicans have loaded the base bill (i.e., the bill reported by the committee) with &lt;a href="https://www.politico.com/newsletters/inside-congress/2024/05/30/trump-trial-house-gop-rules-ouster-00160804"&gt;red meat measures&lt;/a&gt;. Moreover, members of Congress have proposed &lt;a href="https://rules.house.gov/bill/118/hr-FY2025-MilCon"&gt;116 amendments&lt;/a&gt; that the Rules Committee could allow to be considered on the House floor.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;This will be a test case to see whether the House is capable of passing an appropriations bill with only support from Republican members; if so, such legislation will be unable to advance in the Senate without serious changes. It is likely any appropriations bill capable of being enacted into law won't be seriously considered until after the election, and the most we'll see before the October 1 start of the new fiscal year is a bunch of messaging bills and the likely enactment of a continuing resolution to temporarily keep government funded.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;The &lt;a href="https://docs.house.gov/billsthisweek/20240603/RCP_8282_xml.pdf"&gt;other bill&lt;/a&gt; would impose sanctions on the International Criminal Court for investigating, arresting, detaining, or prosecuting any protected person of the U.S. and its allies. This bill, presumably, is aimed at the ICC's &lt;a href="https://news.un.org/en/story/2024/05/1149966"&gt;issuance of a warrant&lt;/a&gt; for Israeli Prime Minister Benjamin Netanyahu.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;Nineteen meetings are &lt;a href="https://www.congress.gov/committee-schedule/weekly/2024/06/03?q=%7B%22chamber%22%3A%22House%22%7D"&gt;scheduled this week&lt;/a&gt; in House Committees. Driving the news will be a COVID Pandemic oversight hearing with Dr. Fauci. I'll be keeping an eye on the Appropriations Committee: there are subcommittee markup meetings occurring before the Homeland Security, State and Foreign Operations, Defense Appropriations, Financial Services and General Government subcommittees. Note that the Defense Appropriations markup will be closed to the public, as will a series of markups concerning the Intelligence Committee's markups of the Intelligence Authorization Act. (The House Appropriations Committee's hearing and markup schedule is &lt;a href="https://appropriations.house.gov/news/press-releases/cole-releases-fiscal-year-2025-markup-schedule"&gt;here&lt;/a&gt;.)&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;The Senate reconvenes &lt;a href="https://www.democrats.senate.gov/2024/05/23/schedule-for-pro-forma-sessions-and-monday-june-3-2024"&gt;on Tuesday&lt;/a&gt; and per usual practice has little information from their official website on what's scheduled --- in this case, a vote on a nominee to the Nuclear Regulatory Committee. But Senator Schumer has sent a &lt;a href="https://www.politico.com/f/?id=0000018f-da92-d531-afdf-db9362760000"&gt;Dear Colleague letter&lt;/a&gt; --- a communication circulated to all members of the Senate and sometimes made publicly available --- declaring the Senate will consider on Wednesday the &lt;a href="https://www.govtrack.us/congress/bills/118/s1999"&gt;Right to Contraception Act&lt;/a&gt; in light of the upcoming two-year anniversary of the Supreme Court decision to curtail constitutional protection for abortion and potentially other matters related to reproductive rights. (We wish Sen. Schumer would publish these letters online as it would make our work a lot easier.)&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;Senate committees scheduled &lt;a href="https://www.congress.gov/committee-schedule/weekly/2024/06/03?q=%7B%22chamber%22%3A%22Senate%22%7D"&gt;eighteen meetings&lt;/a&gt; for this week, half as many as the week before recess. Appropriations is the busiest of the committees, with three hearings, and none of the proceedings appear to be particularly notable.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;The House is &lt;a href="https://www.majorityleader.gov/uploadedfiles/2024_house_calendar_-_one_page_-_revised_april_2024.pdf"&gt;in session&lt;/a&gt; this week and next before taking another week-long break and &lt;a href="https://www.senate.gov/legislative/2024_schedule.htm"&gt;the Senate is in session&lt;/a&gt; for three weeks, with a day off for Juneteenth. Both chambers will end their DC workweek on Wednesday because some members will be joining President Joe Biden in France to commemorate the &lt;a href="https://www.lemonde.fr/en/france/article/2024/05/30/biden-to-make-state-visit-to-france-after-d-day-80th-anniversary-ceremonies_6673161_7.html"&gt;80th anniversary of U.S. forces landing at Normandy&lt;/a&gt; as part of D-Day.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;ICYMI, Sen. Manchin &lt;a href="https://www.politico.com/live-updates/2024/05/31/congress/manchin-independent-west-virginia-senate-governor-00160969?nname=inside-congress&amp;amp;nid=0000014f-1646-d88f-a1cf-5f46b4be0000&amp;amp;nrid=1a3f1abb-3676-4ca7-80a0-d93a12bb5910&amp;amp;nlid=630309"&gt;announced&lt;/a&gt; he has registered as an independent, although he will keep caucusing with Senate Democrats.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;It's not the House or the Senate, but the Congressional Data Task Force, which is a cross-legislative branch effort to modernize congressional technology, will hold its quarterly &lt;a href="https://congressionaldata.org/cdtf-meeting-set-for-june-6-2024/"&gt;public event on Thursday&lt;/a&gt;. Internal and external stakeholders collaborate at these meetings to make more timely and useful information available to folks inside Congress as well as all of us.&lt;/p&gt;      &lt;/div&gt; &lt;/div&gt;  &lt;hr&gt;  &lt;p&gt;    Let us know what you think about these updates    by tooting us on &lt;a rel="me" href="https://mastodon.social/@GovTrack" title="Mastodon"&gt;&lt;i class="fab fa-mastodon"&gt;&lt;/i&gt; Mastodon&lt;/a&gt;    or &lt;a href="https://www.govtrack.us/contact" style="text-decoration: none"&gt;&lt;i class="fas fa-envelope"&gt;&lt;/i&gt; sending us an email&lt;/a&gt;. &lt;/p&gt;    			&lt;/div&gt;</description>
      <media:content url="https://www.govtrack.us/static/images/media_icon.png?20230729" type="image/png"/>
    </item>
